# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: microsegmentation-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] When a cyber-criminal gains unauthorized access to a network, segmentation or “zoning” can provide effective controls to limit further movement across the network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] For example separating the network for Payment Card authorizations from those for Point-of-Service (till) or customer Wi-Fi traffic.
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] A sound security policy entails segmenting the network into multiple zones, with varying security requirements, and rigorously enforcing the policy on what is allowed to move from zone to zone.
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] Finance and Human Resources typically need access via their own VLAN to their application servers because of the confidential nature of the information they process and store.
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] Other groups of personnel may require their own segregated networks, such as server administrators, security administration, managers and executives.
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] Third parties are usually required to have their own segments, with different administration passwords to the main network, to avoid attacks via a compromised, less well protected, third party site.
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] Segregation is typically achieved by a combination of firewalls and VLANs (virtual local area networks).
[src:microsegmentation-network/network-segmentation] Software-defined networking (SDN) can allow the creation and management of micro-segmented networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:microsegmentation-network/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:microsegmentation-network/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] In computing, a **stateful firewall** is a network-based firewall that individually tracks sessions of network connections traversing it.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] **Stateful packet inspection**, also referred to as dynamic packet filtering, is a security feature often used in non-commercial and business networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] A stateful firewall keeps track of the state of network connections, such as TCP streams, UDP datagrams, and ICMP messages, and can apply labels such as *LISTEN*, *ESTABLISHED*, or *CLOSING*.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] State table entries are created for TCP streams or UDP datagrams that are allowed to communicate through the firewall in accordance with the configured security policy.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] Once in the table, all *RELATED* packets of a stored session are streamlined, taking fewer CPU cycles than standard inspection.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] Related packets are also permitted to return through the firewall even if no rule is configured to allow communications from that host.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] If no traffic is seen for a specified time (time-out implementation dependent), the connection is removed from the state table.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] This can lead to applications experiencing unexpected disconnects or half-open TCP connections.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] Applications can be written to send keepalive messages periodically to prevent a firewall from dropping the connection during periods of no activity or for applications which by design have long periods of silence.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] The method of maintaining a session's state depends on the transport protocol being used.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] TCP is a connection-oriented protocol and sessions are established with a three-way handshake using *SYN* packets and ended by sending a *FIN* notification.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] The firewall can use these unique connection identifiers to know when to remove a session from the state table without waiting for a timeout.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] UDP is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not send unique connection-related identifiers while communicating.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] Because of that, a session will only be removed from the state table after the configured time-out.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] UDP hole punching is a technology that leverages this trait to allow for dynamically setting up data tunnels over the internet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] ICMP messages are distinct from TCP and UDP and communicate control information of the network itself.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] A well-known example of this is the ping utility.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] ICMP responses will be allowed back through the firewall.
[src:microsegmentation-network/stateful-firewall] In some scenarios, UDP communication can use ICMP to provide information about the state of the session so ICMP responses related to a UDP session will also be allowed back through.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] A **virtual local area network** (**VLAN**) is a local area network broadcast domain that is partitioned and isolated in a virtual network at the data link layer (OSI layer 2).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] A VLAN behaves like a virtual network switch or network link that can share the same physical structure with other VLANs while staying logically separate from them.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs work by applying tags to network frames that are forwarded within the broadcast domain, creating the appearance and functionality of network traffic that behaves as if it were split between separate networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In this way, VLANs can keep network applications separate despite being connected to the same physical network, and without requiring multiple sets of cabling and networking devices to be deployed.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs allow network administrators to group hosts together even if the hosts are not directly connected to the same network switch.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Because VLAN membership can be configured through software, this can greatly simplify network design and deployment.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Without VLANs, grouping hosts according to their resources requires relocating nodes or rewiring data links.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs allow devices that must be kept separate to share the cabling of a physical network and yet be prevented from directly interacting with one another.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This managed sharing yields gains in simplicity, security, traffic control, and economy.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Many Internet hosting services use VLANs to separate customers' private zones from one another, enabling each customer's servers to be grouped within a single network segment regardless of where the individual servers are located in the data center.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Some precautions are needed to prevent traffic "escaping" from a given VLAN, an exploit known as VLAN hopping.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] To subdivide a network into VLANs, one configures network equipment.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Simpler equipment might partition only each physical port, in which case each VLAN runs over a dedicated network cable.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] More sophisticated devices can mark frames through VLAN tagging, so that a single interconnect (*trunk*) may be used to transport data for multiple VLANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Since VLANs share bandwidth, a VLAN trunk can use link aggregation, quality-of-service prioritization, or both to route data efficiently.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs address issues such as scalability, security, and network management.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Network architects set up VLANs to provide network segmentation.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Routers between VLANs filter broadcast traffic, enhance network security, perform address summarization, and mitigate network congestion.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In a network utilizing broadcasts for service discovery, address assignment and resolution and other services, as the number of peers on a network grows, the frequency of broadcasts also increases.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs can help manage broadcast traffic by forming multiple broadcast domains.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Breaking up a large network into smaller independent segments reduces the amount of broadcast traffic each network device and network segment has to bear.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Switches may not bridge network traffic between VLANs, as doing so would violate the integrity of the VLAN broadcast domain.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs can also help create multiple layer 3 networks on a single physical infrastructure.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs are data link layer (OSI layer 2) constructs, analogous to Internet Protocol (IP) subnets, which are network layer (OSI layer 3) constructs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In an environment employing VLANs, a one-to-one relationship often exists between VLANs and IP subnets, although it is possible to have multiple subnets on one VLAN.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Without VLAN capability, users are assigned to networks based on geography and are limited by physical topologies and distances.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs can logically group networks to decouple the users' network location from their physical location.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] By using VLANs, one can control traffic patterns and react quickly to employee or equipment relocations.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs provide the flexibility to adapt to changes in network requirements and allow for simplified administration.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] A common infrastructure shared across VLAN trunks can provide a measure of security with great flexibility for a comparatively low cost.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Quality of service schemes can optimize traffic on trunk links for real-time (e.g.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] However, VLANs as a security solution should be implemented with great care as they can be defeated unless implemented carefully.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In cloud computing VLANs, IP addresses, and MAC addresses in the cloud are resources that end users can manage.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] To help mitigate security issues, placing cloud-based virtual machines on VLANs may be preferable to placing them directly on the Internet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] After successful experiments with voice over Ethernet from 1981 to 1984, W.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] David Sincoskie joined Bellcore and began addressing the problem of scaling up Ethernet networks.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] At 10 Mbit/s, Ethernet was faster than most alternatives at the time.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] However, Ethernet was a broadcast network and there was no good way of connecting multiple Ethernet networks together.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This limited the total bandwidth of an Ethernet network to 10 Mbit/s and the maximum distance between nodes to a few hundred feet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] By contrast, although the existing telephone network's speed for individual connections was limited to 56 kbit/s (less than one hundredth of Ethernet's speed), the total bandwidth of that network was estimated at 1 Tbit/s (100,000 times greater than Ethernet).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Although it was possible to use IP routing to connect multiple Ethernet networks together, it was expensive and relatively slow.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Sincoskie started looking for alternatives that required less processing per packet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In the process, he independently reinvented transparent bridging, the technique used in modern Ethernet switches.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] However, using switches to connect multiple Ethernet networks in a fault-tolerant fashion requires redundant paths through that network, which in turn requires a spanning tree configuration.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This ensures that there is only one *active* path from any source node to any destination on the network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This causes centrally located switches to become bottlenecks, limiting scalability as more networks are interconnected.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] To help alleviate this problem, Sincoskie invented VLANs by adding a tag (an individual label, such as A, B, C, and so on) to each Ethernet frame.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In this scheme, each switch could be assigned to handle frames of a specific tag and ignore the rest.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] The networks could be interconnected with three spanning trees, one for each color.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] By sending a mix of different frame tags, the aggregate bandwidth could be improved.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Sincoskie referred to this as a *multitree bridge*.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] He and Chase Cotton created and refined the algorithms necessary to make the system feasible.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This *color* is what is now known in the Ethernet frame as the IEEE 802.1Q header, or the VLAN tag.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] While VLANs are commonly used in modern Ethernet networks, they are not used in the manner first envisioned here.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In 1998, Ethernet VLANs were described in the first edition of the IEEE 802.1Q-1998 standard.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This was extended with IEEE 802.1ad to allow nested VLAN tags in service of provider bridging.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This mechanism was improved with IEEE 802.1ah-2008.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Early network designers often segmented physical LANs with the aim of reducing the size of the Ethernet collision domain—thus improving performance.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] When Ethernet switches made this a non-issue (because each switch port is a collision domain), attention turned to reducing the size of the data link layer broadcast domain.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs were first employed to separate several broadcast domains across one physical medium.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] A VLAN can also serve to restrict access to network resources without regard to physical topology of the network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLANs operate at the data link layer of the OSI model.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Administrators often configure a VLAN to map directly to an IP network, or subnet, which gives the appearance of involving the network layer.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Generally, VLANs within the same organization will be assigned different non-overlapping network address ranges.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] There is no issue with separate VLANs using identical overlapping address ranges (e.g. two VLANs each use the private network *192.168.0.0/16*).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] However, it is not possible to route data between two networks with overlapping addresses without delicate IP remapping, so if the goal of VLANs is segmentation of a larger overall organizational network, non-overlapping addresses must be used in each separate VLAN.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] A basic switch that is not configured for VLANs has VLAN functionality disabled or permanently enabled with a *default VLAN* that contains all ports on the device as members.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] The default VLAN typically uses VLAN identifier 1.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Every device connected to one of its ports can send packets to any of the others.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Separating ports by VLAN groups separates their traffic very much like connecting each group using a distinct switch for each group.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Remote management of the switch requires that the administrative functions be associated with one or more of the configured VLANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In the context of VLANs, the term *trunk* denotes a network link carrying multiple VLANs, which are identified by labels (or *tags*) inserted into their packets.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Such trunks must run between *tagged ports* of VLAN-aware devices, so they are often switch-to-switch or switch-to-router links rather than links to hosts.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] (Note that the term 'trunk' is also used for what Cisco calls "channels" : Link Aggregation or Port Trunking).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] A router (Layer 3 device) serves as the backbone for network traffic going across different VLANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] It is only when the VLAN port group is to extend to another device that tagging is used.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Since communications between ports on two different switches travel via the uplink ports of each switch involved, every VLAN containing such ports must also contain the uplink port of each switch involved, and traffic through these ports must be tagged.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Switches typically have no built-in method to indicate VLAN to port associations to someone working in a wiring closet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] It is necessary for a technician to either have administrative access to the device to view its configuration, or for VLAN port assignment charts or diagrams to be kept next to the switches in each wiring closet.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] The protocol most commonly used today to support VLANs is IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] The IEEE 802.1 working group defined this method of multiplexing VLANs in an effort to provide multivendor VLAN support.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Prior to the introduction of the 802.1Q standard, several proprietary protocols existed, such as Cisco Inter-Switch Link (ISL) and 3Com's Virtual LAN Trunk (VLT).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Cisco also implemented VLANs over FDDI by carrying VLAN information in an IEEE 802.10 frame header, contrary to the purpose of the IEEE 802.10 standard.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Both ISL and IEEE 802.1Q perform *explicit tagging* – the frame itself is tagged with VLAN identifiers.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] ISL uses an external tagging process that does not modify the Ethernet frame, while 802.1Q uses a frame-internal field for tagging, and therefore does modify the basic Ethernet frame structure.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This internal tagging allows IEEE 802.1Q to work on both access and trunk links using standard Ethernet hardware.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Under IEEE 802.1Q, the maximum number of VLANs on a given Ethernet network is 4,094 (4,096 values provided by the 12-bit VID field minus reserved values at each end of the range, 0 and 4,095).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This does not impose the same limit on the number of IP subnets in such a network since a single VLAN can contain multiple IP subnets.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1ad extends the number of VLANs supported by adding support for multiple, nested VLAN tags.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] IEEE 802.1aq (Shortest Path Bridging) expands the VLAN limit to 16 million.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Both improvements have been incorporated into the IEEE 802.1Q standard.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Inter-Switch Link (ISL) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to interconnect switches and maintain VLAN information as traffic travels between switches on trunk links.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] ISL is provided as an alternative to IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] ISL is available only on some Cisco equipment and has been deprecated.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLAN Trunking Protocol (VTP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol that propagates the definition of VLANs on the whole local area network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VTP is available on most of the Cisco Catalyst Family products.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] The comparable IEEE standard in use by other manufacturers is GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP) or the more recent Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol is an application of Multiple Registration Protocol that allows automatic configuration of VLAN information on network switches.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Specifically, it provides a method to dynamically share VLAN information and configure the needed VLANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLAN membership can be established either statically or dynamically.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Static VLANs are also referred to as port-based VLANs.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Static VLAN assignments are created by assigning ports to a VLAN.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the device automatically assumes the VLAN of the port.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] If the user changes ports and needs access to the same VLAN, the network administrator must manually make a port-to-VLAN assignment for the new connection.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Dynamic VLANs are created using software or by protocol.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] With a VLAN Management Policy Server (VMPS), an administrator can assign switch ports to VLANs dynamically based on information such as the source MAC address of the device connected to the port or the username used to log onto that device.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] As a device enters the network, the switch queries a database for the VLAN membership of the port that device is connected to.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Protocol methods include Multiple VLAN Registration Protocol (MVRP) and the somewhat obsolete GARP VLAN Registration Protocol (GVRP).
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] In a switch that supports protocol-based VLANs, traffic may be handled on the basis of its protocol.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] Essentially, this segregates or forwards traffic from a port depending on the particular protocol of that traffic; traffic of any other protocol is not forwarded on the port.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] This allows, for example, IP and IPX traffic to be automatically segregated by the network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] VLAN cross connect (CC or VLAN-XC) is a mechanism used to create Switched VLANs, VLAN CC uses IEEE 802.1ad frames where the S Tag is used as a Label as in MPLS.
[src:microsegmentation-network/virtual-lan] IEEE approves the use of such a mechanism in part 6.11 of IEEE 802.1ad-2005.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] ZTA is implemented by establishing identity verification, validating device compliance prior to granting access, and ensuring least privilege access to only explicitly-authorized resources.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] Most modern corporate networks consist of many interconnected zones, cloud services and infrastructure, connections to remote and mobile environments, and connections to non-conventional IT, such as IoT devices.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The traditional approach by trusting users and devices within a notional "corporate perimeter" or via a VPN connection is commonly not sufficient in the complex environment of a corporate network.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The zero trust architecture has been proposed for use in specific areas such as supply chains.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The principles of zero trust can be applied to data access, and to the management of data.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] This brings about zero trust data security where every request to access the data needs to be authenticated dynamically and ensure least privileged access to resources.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In order to determine if access can be granted, policies can be applied based on the attributes of the data, who the user is, and the type of environment using Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC).
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] This zero trust data security approach can protect access to the data.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] Several definitions of zero trust have been proposed since the term was first used in 1994.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In April 1994, the term "zero trust" was coined by Stephen Paul Marsh in his doctoral thesis on computer security at the University of Stirling.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] Marsh's work studied trust as something finite that can be described mathematically, asserting that the concept of trust transcends human factors such as morality, ethics, lawfulness, justice, and judgement.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The problems of the Smartie or M&M model of the network (the precursor description of de-perimeterisation) was described by a Sun Microsystems engineer in a Network World article in May 1994, who described firewalls' perimeter defence, as a hard shell around a soft centre, like a Cadbury Egg.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In 2001 the first version of the OSSTMM (Open Source Security Testing Methodology Manual) was released and this had some focus on trust.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] Version 3 which came out around 2007 has a whole chapter on Trust which says "Trust is a Vulnerability" and talks about how to apply the OSSTMM 10 controls based on Trust levels.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In 2018, the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and National Cybersecurity Center of Excellence (NCCoE) published NIST SP 800-207 – zero trust architecture.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The publication defines zero trust as a collection of concepts and ideas designed to reduce the uncertainty in enforcing accurate, per-request access decisions in information systems and services in the face of a network viewed as compromised.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] A Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) is an enterprise's cyber security plan that utilizes zero trust concepts and encompasses component relationships, workflow planning, and access policies.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] Therefore, a zero trust enterprise is the network infrastructure (physical and virtual) and operational policies that are in place for an enterprise as a product of a zero trust architecture plan.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology**.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The ZT-Kipling methodology moves beyond the foundational principles of Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) by defining a set of five mandatory, iterative steps.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] This methodology treats ZT as a continual and iterative process..
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] The core of the methodology’s systematic nature lies in its integration of the Kipling Criteria: what, why, when, where, who, and how.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] This entire process is repeated throughout the lifetime of a protected surface, which must be clearly defined in Step #1 of the methodology.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] TS 104 102 establishes the ZT-Kipling methodology as a systematic and cyclical governance framework for Zero Trust.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In 2010 the term Zero Trust model was used by analyst John Kindervag of Forrester Research to denote stricter cybersecurity programs and access control within corporations.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In 2003 the challenges of defining the perimeter to an organisation's IT systems was highlighted by the Jericho Forum, discussing the trend of what was then given the name "de-perimeterisation".
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In response to Operation Aurora, a Chinese APT attack throughout 2009, Google started to implement a zero-trust architecture referred to as BeyondCorp an internal initiative to implement a zero trust security model that eliminated the need for a privileged VPN.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] Throughout the 2010s, zero trust architectures became more prevalent, driven in part by increased adoption of mobile and cloud services.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In 2019 the United Kingdom National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) recommended that network architects consider a Zero Trust approach for new IT deployments, particularly where significant use of cloud services is planned.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In the United States, Executive Order 14028 (May 2021) directed federal agencies to adopt zero trust architectures, and the Office of Management and Budget subsequently issued memorandum M-22-09 requiring agencies to meet specific zero trust security goals by the end of fiscal year 2024.
[src:microsegmentation-network/zero-trust-security-model] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology** to be used to achieve Zero Trust security posture.
